Nov 12 2009 	The Carlton Hotel is the best stay in SF for the price and location! Dyan Vancouver B.C. Canada	Like several people before us we had a perfect stay at the Carlton from start to finish. We were there for 5 nights from Nov. 4th to 9th. The staff was of very friendly, and helpful like others mentioned. When we arrived they worked it out so that our friend who also booked a room for the same time was just down the hall in #610 and we were in #608. This worked out well for planning our days together and having a coffee in the morning etc. None of us found the walls paper thin like some have said. The view wasn't great but we didn't care. You could hear the doors in the hallways and water running from other showers but neither were out of the ordinary. We could hear sirens from time to time from the nearby fire station and hospital but it wasn't bad. I do sleep with earplugs in all the time anyways because I'm a light sleeper. The room was not too small with a little writing desk and biggish closet for a hotel and a personal safe in the closet, with iron and ironing board. The bed was sooo comfortable! and the rooms kept clean. The room was also the perfect temperature, not too hot or too cold. Nice Moroccan, modern decor and there is filtered water in the lobby if you want instead of the tap water. There is a water jug you can fill up and bring back to your room. There is a coffee maker in the room with complimentary coffee. I wish they also had a few tea bags ,it's maybe something they could add. We would grab a coffee and yummy almond croissant from a little place up at 916 Sutter called Dolce Gelato, apparently they have the best Gelato in the world according to others but we never tried it. The Carlton is a green hotel so you can have your sheets and towels done everyday, or if you want or save water and energy by not having them done daily they have a little sign to put out for the cleaning staff to tell them what you would like. They also have recycling bins in the rooms which is great for paper and bottles etc.There are 2 computers in the Lobby area for guests. You get 20 minutes free per day which is super! You just have to run your Visa through the slot on the side of the computer and a timer will come up on the screen for 20 mins. at the end of the 20 mins. a note will come on the screen asking if you want to purchase more time or terminate, I always terminated which is no charge on your Visa. 20 mins. is great just to check your mail etc. The free wine tasting in the evenings from 5:30 to 6:00pm is awesome. They will refill your wine as well if you want more than a glass no problem. It's nice to mingle with the other guests and it's very popular!! The front desk also opened a couple of corked bottles of wine for us which we had bought at a store because we had no corkscrew, and asked if we wanted wine bottles to take to the room. We thought the location was great, lots of buses go nearby and not too far from Market St. and Union square. Good shops and restaurant nearby. I know there are some rough spots in the Tenderloin area but I think every city has that, we had no problems. Finally I must say that we went to the SAHA Restaurant as recommended by others and were not disappointed. The food was amazing! All the dishes were good, and they had Vegan options for our friend who is a Vegan. We went twice, the second time was for a couple of appy's and desert. We all tried Chocopear (Chocolate &amp; Pear mousse with poached pear), Slap ya mama (Roasted fruit, date &amp; almond marzipan, and chocolate wrapped in phyllo and baked), Warm Chocolate Cake (Served with gelato, it's the best chocolate cake ever!!! ,Knaffe (Classic Middle Eastern dessert consisting of layers of Arabic cheese &amp; shredded phyllo with syrup) My mouth is watering just thinking about these.. I can't rave enough about all the dishes we had including main courses. They also have a breakfast menu which had Vegan options and looked good. They restaurant was always quite busy. Not huge portions and but a reasonable amount and price for the fantasic flavor sensations there. So I would just say &quot;stay here&quot; next time you are in San Francisco it's a FABULOUS Hotel!Dyan, from Vancouver, B.C. Canada	
Nov 11 2009 	A Jewel of a Hotel - and Green Too	We've stayed in plenty of San Francisco hotels, from fancy (on various company nickels) to fleabags. Hotel Carlton was definitely the nicest. From the moment we checked in and Theo handed us a map and a copy of the Bay Guardian while other guests were enjoying the free wine reception in the lobby, we knew we had hit on something special. We ended up having a terrific three-day stay at the Carlton. The room, decorated with lovely Middle Eastern furnishings and tasteful global art, was good-sized (large enough for us, anyway) and had a huge walk-in closet with a safe for valuables. The king-size bed was extremely comfortable: no backache, even after three nights! The location was great, about a 10-minute walk to Union Square and an affordable cab ride to other parts of the city. The in-hotel restaurant, Saha, gave us and our two foodie friends a memorable meal at a surprising price point. The hotel is also environmentally aware, which is very important to us. Our only complaint was that the person in the room next door whined to the front desk that we had the TV on too loud (it was at a normal volume) at 4 p.m.! However, the desk staff were very apologetic and offered to give us another room, if we wanted. Fortunately, our overly sensitive next-door neighbour checked out early the next morning, so we stayed put. We thought the situation was handled very well. The upshot: Unless your idea of a nice hotel is a Westin or Hilton, you will enjoy the Hotel Carlton.	
Nov 7 2009 	Quite a reasonable hotel in an expensive city	The variability of the reviews for this hotel show how people's expectations can vary. I found this hotel to be an excellent choice when you consider the difficulty of finding a reasonably priced hotel within walking distance of Union Square. Yes, it's an old building, and you can hear street noises, and the neighborhood isn't Nob Hill (although it's nearby). It's a good price; it's well cared-for; the staff members are helpful; the restaurant is good; it's a reasonable walk to all sorts of great places (many straight uphill, of course). I would and probably will return to this hotel, and I suggest that those with reasonable expectations will enjoy their stay.	
