end staying nearer to Union Square or nearer Fishermans Wharf (will be worth the extra few bucks). I can't fault the staff though. They were all really nice and helpful. They did a wine reception in the evening which is a nice touch too.The Fly bar next door is great for food and drink. We had a couple of really nice pizzas and there is a good choice of beers.	
Sep 30 2009 	Comfortable cozy retreat close to the action of Union Sqaure	We stayed at the Hotel Carlton (part of the Joie de Vivre group of hotels) for four nights in mid November 2008 in the first week of our holiday which was to drive from San Francisco down to San Diego and then on to L.A. Initially, on arrival in San Francisco we did not have a car and took the BART train from the airport to the centre.Upon check in we were given a map of the city and told where the main sights and attractions were and which area to avoid namely the Tenderloin district. However we had discovered this area already from making our way from the BART station to the hotel. Rather than taking a taxi direct from the airport, we decided to take the BART (which did save a few dollars) and in trying to work out which stop would be closest to the hotel, decided to get off at the Civic Centre stop. This proved a bit of a mistake (but an unforgettable experience nonetheless!), as we dragged our cases up the escalator from the train station we tried to look for a taxi but could not find a vacant one (and there weren't that many about). So we decided to walk in the direction of the hotel and tried to pick up a taxi en-route. As we hauled our luggage past the Civic Centre there was a demonstration going on and the roads were closed, which may have explained the lack of taxis. Walking in the direction of the hotel took us straight through the Tenderloin district. It is a rough area but luckily it was around 3 o'clock on a Saturday afternoon so didn't encounter any problems. The hotel itself is outside the Tenderloin district and it’s amazing the difference a couple of streets can make. In an odd way it gave us the opportunity to see a part of San Fran, where most other tourists would never go which was one positive. Our room was located on the fifth floor. Everything was in good working order and kept extremely clean and tidy. The room was very spacious and contained a huge king size bed. Also in the room were an ironing board &amp; iron, TV, Hairdryer, coffee maker and a Safety deposit box. There was also a bin just for recycling, which show their environmental ethos. Some reviews state how thin the walls are in the hotel, and to an extent this may be true, but only once did it come to our attention, when the occupants of the room next door decided to have an argument over how much money they had spent in one day. (Yes I could actually hear every single word spoken!). However, it did not affect our overall stay.Within the hotel is a restaurant, which we only used once for breakfast on the first day of our stay. The breakfast - ordered from the menu - was typically American which included cereals, pastries, toast or a cooked breakfast from the menu. As far as the food itself was concerned - the breakfast we ate was fine - nothing spectacular but nice all the same.Located just outside the restaurant was a water vending machine (free to use), which was great to top up our water bottle before a day of exploring the city and the internet point, although the internet was not free to use.The location of the hotel was very close to Union Square – about a 10 minute walk along Sutter Street and from there a cable car can easily be caught to take you over the hill and down to Fisherman’s Wharf.The hotel also hosted a reception evening during our stay. We didn’t make it to this as it started at 17:30 and we were still out for the day. It appeared to be a chance for the guests and staff to get to know one another and share some experiences, along with a free glass of wine.Overall we booked our stay in this hotel to explore the heart of San Francisco and the Hotel Carlton did not disappoint in providing an excellent and comfortable retreat from which to do this.	
