Sep 8 2009 	Budget Chic - but very loud!	I wanted to love this hotel – I would say I ended up more than liking it, but not quite loving it. As others have mentioned, the staff people are warm and professional and the rooms are clean and well-appointed in a sort of basic way. (Think new IKEA furniture.) My only real gripe is the noise. Based on other tripadvisor reviews, I knew it could be an issue, so I asked for a room away from the elevators, and the staff accommodated. Still, I woke up every two or three hours both nights, despite the fact that I am not a particularly light sleeper. Every time someone entered or left their room, the sound of the door closing woke me up. Even when I wore earplugs, I woke up from just the vibration! The building is old and I’m not sure what can be done about it, but it was definitely a bummer. I also woke up when the telephone in the next room rang! Again, I am a totally middle of the road sleeper – not heavy, not light. It’s just that the walls are thin, and the doors are really heavy. Light sleepers should definitely look elsewhere.That said, I wouldn’t count this hotel out for everyone. It has a fun and relaxed vibe, and you get a lot of bang for your buck. I paid right around $100/night, and feel like it was a good value. It’s missing a lot of amenities – plush towels, robes, room service, etc – but it doesn’t advertise itself as a luxury hotel. I’d recommend this hotel to folks who are watching their pennies, but for whom the hotel experience is an important part of their vacation. For light sleepers or those looking for luxury, I’d probably recommend other hotels in the Joie de Vivre chain – some advertise themselves as a bit higher end, and based on the service at the Hotel Carlton, I’d be confident that they’d deliver.	
