Aug 25 2009 	Felt right at home - UK reviewer	My partner and I took a 15 day trip to California/Nevada incorporating LA, San Fran and Vegas. The Hotel Carlton in San Francisco was our second stop.This was my first visit to the USA and so I had no previous experience to base this trip upon. I enjoyed LA but after 4 nights I felt ready to move on and we took the short internal flight up the coast to San Francisco - we were not disappointed!As soon as we arrived at the hotel we were greeted by the front desk as if we were old friends - &quot;We were wondering when you were going to show up&quot; was the greeting, but not delivered with any sarcasm or the over-friendly schmultz that I sometimes feel as a Brit when meeting American's who work in the service industry - it was just really nice and we felt at home straightaway.The decor of the whole hotel is really interesting. The walls are decorated with pictures and art works from across the globe and the lifts (decked out with a massive world map) were covered in post cards on all sides (I may send one myself from Nottingham and see if they stick it in the lift by the next time we visit). Our room was simply beautiful. It was not massive. The television was not huge. It was not palatial by any means... but then whose home is? And this is what the Hotel Carlton felt like - a home, which, when you are travelling to new places, is sometimes exactly what you want!Our bed was really comfortable and was remade everyday with a yellow and orange cover/pillow combo, which might sound a bit garish, but in actual fact made the room appear really stylishly fitted out and very trendy in contrast to the aqua coloured blinds and fittings. We had a safe in the room which you could program with your own code (a must if you don't want to carry your passport, iPod, traveller’s chqs, etc., everywhere with you). The bathroom was more than ample for our needs and was cleaned daily, with our towels being replaced as often as we left them in the bath for collection.We came to San Francisco to see the sites (ie: Fisherman's Wharf, Alcatraz, The Golden Gate Bridge, etc.) and so my partner and I have been baffled by the many silly people who seem to come on to tripadvisor to say &quot;the television was too small&quot; or &quot;I didn't like the kettle&quot;. Seriously guys, if kettles and televisions are what you get excited about then stay at home and save the money you would have spent on travelling to buy a top of the range TV, toaster, kettle, electric back-scratcher, etc.,etc. Having said the previous, the TV and kettle were both adequate. The kettle boiled water and the tv showed TV shows (what more do you want?!?!? - perhaps less adverts, but that’s an issue for US TV networks and not The Hotel Carlton!)We arrived at San Fran in Union Square and so this, by our first timer perceptions, always felt like the centre of San Fran. It took us between 20 and 30 minutes to do the walk from Union Square to the hotel (depending on luggage, amount of alcohol drank, etc.) and this was slightly further than I imagined we would be. The walk, as in many places in SF, is rather a hilly one, but as we are both physically fit and able we didn't mind this too much and it also meant that we were away from the majority of noise that SF has to offer. The only sounds I was able to hear in the night were the fog horn on the SF bay and the occasional cop car/fire truck (think there must be a depot somewhere nearby) but the noise was not so much as to become an annoyance and you'll get these sounds in any major city in any country.The daily wine receptions were one of the reasons that we chose this hotel and these did not disappoint. We always tried to get back to our hotel, or make sure we were just leaving, between 5.30pm and 6pm so that we could enjoy these. Neither of us drinks red so I am unable to comment on it but the white and rose was very, very nice indeed (with the rose being the slightly sweeter of the two). It was a lovely way to end the day by sitting in the foyer and having a glass of wine whilst flicking through one of the many interesting books they had, especially if you'd been on your feet a lot that day! Alternatively, it was a nice way to start the evening if you were going out for a meal. We also got chatting to a few other guests at this time and as people were mingling it just went to enhancing the friendly ambience of the place.Although a lot of the main attractions and restaurants are located a fair walk away from The Carlton there is an excellent but busy (probably due to its excellence) little pub next door called the Fly Bar (if memory serves) which has a great happy hour serving drinks and pizzas fairly inexpensively (check out the local ale “Anchor steam”) and this was useful when we wanted a cheap night away from the centre of SF.Internet access was available but required a payment after the first free 20 minutes but this was easily avoided by using separate debit/credit cards every time we wanted to log on - and as we only stayed 4 days this never became a problem and we only used the internet quickly to check up on essentials (onward reservations for rental cars, flights, etc.)All in all we really enjoyed our time in SF. The Hotel Carlton is a home away from home and we loved it. We would heartily recommend it to anyone who really wants to experience San Francisco and enjoy the spirit of this amazing city. The only slight downside is its distance from the Union Square area but we found that the short walk was what allowed us to take in the true atmosphere of the city and to really fall in love with it. At times I was seriously considering the implications of upping sticks from the UK and moving here - I felt so comfortable and knowing we had a place like The Carlton to stay at, I know, played a major part in this perception.Some tips about sightseeing in SF:*Find a decent map (ask at the front desk - the one they gave us was exactly what we needed)*Alcatraz - book online, in advance or take your chances with the queues*Take a good pair of trainers - you will be doing lots of walking (and the tram is always busy and not that cheap)*Use &quot;citysight-seeing&quot; for any bus tour made of SF. We used them for LA and really enjoyed it but chose a different firm for our tour of SF and regretted it.(I'm sorry to say I can't recall the name at present - I'll post if I can find the tickets or remember the name)) but whilst we waited for our tour bus for 45 minutes in the Fisherman's Wharf area city sight-seeing buses passed our growing crowd and the clientele looked comfortable. When our bus arrived it was late, overcrowded and some of us had to sit down stairs as we crossed the GG Bridge. (Rubbish service!)*When the Golden Gate Bridge is clear of fog ...GO! We spent the only clear day on Alcatraz and assumed the day after would be clear for the bridge... it was in the morning, but within 15 minutes thick, thick fog covered it even though it was a sunny day - still go on it even if it is foggy... still worth it!*Ask Carlton staff for restaurant tips - they know the area.*Visit the Starlight rooms for a great view of SF*Take a walk to Chinatown - don't stop at the gate...it only just begins there!*Clothes shopping around Union Square is great - I 'm a typical bloke who hates clothes shopping, but there are some real bargains to be found in SF so take advantage, especially if you are a UK citizen who is sick of being ripped off by the ludicrous prices we pay at home! (e.g. Levi's jeans $55 = £30. £75 in UK)Enjoy your trip to San Francisco! If you loved it, and the Hotel Carlton, half as much as we did, it won't be your last visit!	
Aug 25 2009 	Gem of a Hotel - Can't wait to go back!	After leaving LA behind and getting an internal flight up to San Francisco I was a little nervous as I had such a great stay in LA but once arriving in San Francisco not only did I fall in love with the place but I fell in love with the hotel Carlton! Its quirky, its cosy and quite frankly a rare Gem that you only find occasionaly if at all. The staff are fantastic, each and every one of them helped us at some point with advice on places to eat, places to see, transport to use - the management should be very pleased they have these guys on their staff as they are great.We loved the wine reception between 5.30 - 6.00pm every evening as it meant we could have a relaxing glass of wine in the comfy reception area after a long day out sight seeing. It also meant that you could meet and chat to people. We met a couple from New Zealand who were on a 3 month trip around the world and ended up having dinner with them which was lovely!Our room was great, very comfy bed and plenty of room for all our stuff, bathroom clean and thats what you need! I would reccomend the bar next door but one or maybe its next door thinking about it! Fly its called and its a great, happy hour until 7pm and the food is delicious and cheap! Especially when you have been walking about all day up and down hills you sometimes just don't want to venture into Union Sq so nip next door and sample this place you will not be disappointed although at weekends it gets very busy but I can see why!If you fancy a mexican try Colibri its just off Union Square and its just fabulous a bit on the pricey side but for a really good meal definately try it!Trip wise make sure you do Alcatraz and use the headphone sets as its really interesting, you won't appreciate walking around it yourself without them. (They are already included in the price). Golden Gate Bridge a must for obvious reasons! Pier 39 with all the great little food places, shops and of course the sea 