Apr 15 2009 	Great Value	I enjoyed the Hotel Carlton. I did not need the bells and whistles, as I was in San Francisco for the first time and did not intend to spend much time in my room. Just some thoughts I have overall...Above all, it is CLEAN. The rooms have pitchers if you'd like to fill them with water which you can get downstairs by the restaurant. The rooms are on the smaller side (we had two beds), but really no different from any other city hotel (the ones in NYC are tiny!!). Beds were huge and very comfortable with a million pillows. The bathroom is clean, however it doesn't have much room to put your stuff on (and with two girls, you can bet we had a lot!). We had to put half the stuff in the bathroom, the other half on the desk in our room. Not a big deal but something to note. OH the elevators are a little scary. The hotel has 2, and one of them is the kind you have to open a door to get into it. I saw a woman standing there pushing the button repeatedly because she didn't realize the elevator was there until i mentioned it to her. Kinda weird. They have one restaurant on premise, Saha, an Arabic fusion restaurant. I normally try not to eat in hotel restaurants but one night we were feeling lazy and thought it would be interesting to try. Turned out to be one of the best meals we had! Highly recommend the ravioli, the sauce made it unbelievable.I never felt unsafe walking around and i scare easy, lol. I think the 'safe' area is making a right out of the hotel. That is where everything was (Union Square, Chinatown, etc) so that is my assumption. Just don't turn left when you leave the hotel! Haha. It was easy to get to the trolley from the hotel, it was maybe a little further than i would have liked but made sleeping very easy as it was very quiet in the area. A TIP: If you are planning to use the trolley at least a few times a day, I would suggest buying a MUNI passport, depending on how long you are in the area. They have several different options, we bought the 3 day pass for $18 in front of Ghiradelli Square but I'm sure you can get them at other places. ONE trolley ride costs $5, so even if you took it 4 times it would already pay for itself. It's also great because occasionally a trolley will get stuck on the tracks. When one gets stuck, none of them move. I'm not sure if your money was returned if you decide to get out and walk instead but because we had the passports this wasn't a problem. The MUNI is also good for buses so it's a bargain, since we used it to get to Golden Gate Park. The front desk was so helpful, when we needed to find out how to get to Golden Gate Park, he told us exactly where to take the bus, which bus number to take, and gave us a map so we could be doubly sure. Anything we asked for they made sure to help us out in any way they could.TRANSPORTATION: We took a cab from the airport to the hotel and it cost us almost $50! (wasn't expecting it to be that high) The hotel should have a link to a shuttle service from the airport, I think it was Lori's Shuttle(?), which cost about $15 a person! We did fly into SFO later (around midnight) so I don't think the shuttle would have been available anyway, but for anyone who will flying in at normal hours. I think this shuttle service also picks up for other hotels, not just the Carlton. If you are looking to be pampered this is not the hotel for you. But if you are looking for a clean, comfortable place to sleep that is not too far from Union Square/other areas, this is the hotel for you.	
Apr 10 2009 	Perfect place to stay if you want to see the city	I got such a great deal on this hotel I couldn't even believe it. $59 per night! I booked a double room and it was tiny but the bed was comfortable. The bathroom was very clean and they had a shampoo, conditioner and body wash dispenser. Take note if you are not used to soft water bring some hair products with you! Between the water and the humidity my hair was really frizzy. I thought the decor was very nice and cultured. The building is historic so if you are looking for 'brand new' book yourself at the Westin or some place like that. We walked all over the city during the day and took cabs at night. I would suggest taking a straight walking path down Sutter to downtown if that is where you are going. In this city if you go one street over depending on where you are there are many homeless people. We were not bothered by them but I did hear from people that they can be very agressive. They seem to flock towards the shopping/downtown district during the day time so pay attention. The hotel offers free table wine in the lobby at 5:30pm every day. We referred to it as &quot;wine-thirty&quot;. They will refill your glass as much as you want but be aware that they only do this for 30 min. and then take it away. At night taking cabs is ideal. The hotel will hail you a cab in 2 seconds. We paid about $10-$12 to go one way across town. Check out the Mission and North Beach areas at night. We had coffee in the morning at the restaurant that is connected to the hotel but we never ate dinner there. The coffee was very strong and very good. We used the computers in the lobby and although we had to pay to use them it was convenient to have them there because we used them to book a trip to the Muir Woods and Sonoma. The staff at the hotel was very nice and I had no problems - check out was a breeze. We were going to take the free hotel car to the train at Powell Street and something was wrong with the car so the hotel gave us $8 for a cab. That was super nice of them! ps. I do not agree with the other review that says seeing the photos of 3rd world people on the walls was stressful. If you think those photos were stressful how about the large amount of homeless people completely passed out on the street all over the city? Get a grip!	
Apr 9 2009 	Don't know why it's rated so highly	I was initially very pleased to see what a high rating Hotel Carlton (HC) got on tripadvisor--after all, the travelers are the experts. However, when we arrived, I was taken aback at how old the hotel felt, despite the updated global decor. As most everyone has already mentioned, the staff are great. We booked a Queen room and were given a higher floor, upon request for an upgrade; however were not offered a King room. I think what bothered me most about the hotel was the fact that there was art that was suggestive of folks who were struggling in the developing world. Don't get me wrong--both my partner and I work in non-profit and are all about working w/populations that are marginalized. However, when I'm on vacation, I'd like to feel like it's okay to splurge and take care of myself. I suppose that's a pretty disintegrated view of life, but I suppose it would have been nice to feel like the room was a place where I could really relax and enjoy. As others had mentioned already, there are some dodgey areas to walk through when trying to navigate around the city by foot--so just be aware of that. I also didn't like the fact that parking was a whopping $35/night at an open lot across the street, particularly in that area. I don't think I'd go back to Hotel Carlton.	
Apr 8 2009 	Great Service Thin Walls Not the Best Neighborhood	It wasn't the best introduction to San Francisco. The cab driver took us right through the middle of the Tenderloin District which is on the way to the hotel if you take a direct route off the freeway from the airport. The Tenderloin district is a &quot;pit of despair&quot; to quote our Frommers Guide Book. (We read about it after we got to the hotel.) The hotel is right on the edge of this district, and so we thought we had made a big mistake to book a hotel in such a bad neighborhood. (We didn't know anything about this when we booked.) To give the hotel credit, the rooms were a decent size and very clean. The walls, however, are very thin, and we had a situation in the middle of the night where the people next door kept us awake just by talking. The service is excellent. The hotel staff at the reception could not have been more helpful. As we had not paid a very high price for this hotel, we learned once again that you get what you pay for. I think in hindsight that we should have booked a more expensive hotel and done more research on the location of the hotel. I would not recommend this hotel to a friend only because of its location. If they were on a tight budget, I would tell them it is decent hotel for the money, but to be very careful where they walk. San Francisco downtown, by the way, is very typical of large American cities, which means you always want to know where your purse or wallet is, and to avoid eye contact with the many homeless and panhandlers.	
