Feb 23 2009 	Favourite hotel in North America an incredible place to stay!	After debating between several districts in San Francisco in which to stay, we chose the Carlton Hotel initially due to it's location and popular reviews. We weren't sure whether it would be more ideal to stay nearer Fisherman's Wharf, or maybe in the SOMA district. We were thrilled with our choice of the Carlton located in Lower Nob Hill. It was perfect walking distance to all attractions that San Francisco is known for, and we felt like we were right in the heart of the city, and a beautiful district too! The front desk team were attentive, approachable, friendly and professional. They went above and beyond what was necessary to make our stay a great one, and exceeded our expectations. J.P., Adrian and Theo are fantastic assets to the Carlton, as was everyone else who I didn't get the names of. We were truly impressed with the service, which far surpassed many of the other hotels I've stayed at. Our upgraded deluxe room was newly renovated, impeccably clean, and even the shower had a great view of the city through its large window. It was quite in the evenings, which surprised us given it's right downtown. There was a brand new LCD flatscreen TV, a large walk-in closet, with classy and comfortable furniture. Even the hallways throughout the hotel were eclectically decorated and eye-capturing, unlike many other hotels which can be vanilla, this one was definitely more raspberry truffle! We were encouraged to take advantage of the complimentary wine reception in the foyer during the evenings, which were well attended and enjoyable. There was a red, white and white zinfandel to choose from, and we were being topped up throughout the reception by the server who was attentive and kind. The live music, comfortable ambience, fireplace roaring between the oversize sofas, started each evening off to a great start!We were pleased with how 'green' the hotel was, along with a recycling receptacle in our room, there was definitely care taken to ensure a smaller carbon footprint without sacrificing any charm. It was interesting to discover that this hotel employs solar panels to capitalize on sunny California's natural energy source...bonus!The tenderloin district was somewhat nearby, which the front desk staff advised us to avoid in the evenings and clearly showed us on a map where it was located. We always felt safe while walking after dark, no complaints there, but it would have been nice to explore all 360 degrees of the city surrounding the hotel rather than having to avoid one nearby area. Room service wasn't available, but I hope it will be added on in the future, because the Saha restaurant looks fantastic!	
