Jan 12 2009 	Friendly fun and affordable	This was our first trip to San Francisco, and the Hotel Carlton proved to be a fantastic base for the trip. We were mainly there for the Macworld Expo, but did a lot of sightseeing too. The Hotel is well-located - a short walk away from Union Square where all the main shops and restaurants are. It's also not too far to Chinatown and Little Italy (with trams going from Union Square, though the walk is pleasant). Although I was initially concerned that the hotel might be a little close to the Tenderloin, this was a non-issue. We were told as soon as we arrived which area to avoid at night, but - as another reviewer on TripAdvisor said - you'd be unlikely to head that way anyway. There are a few homeless people around, but that's true of everywhere else in SF we went, and it's no more than you would find in any city (in fact, San Francisco is one of the least intimidating cities I've ever visited). For the price, the Hotel is in a fabulous location.As for the hotel itself... It was just brilliant. The staff were friendly and helpful. They also seem to take note of when you are going out - no one ever knocked to clean our room, but it would be spotless whenever we returned from going out. Our room was on the seventh floor, at the back. It was quiet and much better appointed than I had expected. The beds were firm and very comfortable, the bathroom was clean, the shower was decent and the decor was tasteful. The room could get warm (considering it is midwinter) but the ceiling fan sorted that out. Other reviewers have mentioned the thin walls, and I was concerned that things would be too noisy - but again, it was a non-issue. Although I could hear people moving about in the corridor, and the TV and talking from next door at one point, things were generally quiet; certainly, no worse than some of the terraced houses or flats in which I've lived. So don't let the thin walls put you off this excellent hotel!I should mention the wine evenings... From 5.30-6pm every day there is free wine (in another review somebody said there was no red wine, but when we went there was a selection of red, white or sweet rosé). This was brilliant, and really added to the atmosphere and buzz of the place. Many of the guests would come down from their rooms, sit around on the sofas in front of the blazing fire, supping wine whilst Theo - one of the friendly and helpful concierges - played the keyboard. It was a great way to start the evening.We also tried the Saha (the hotel's restaurant) - it is definitely worth checking out while you are there. I'm vegetarian and the meal I chose at the Saha was one of the best veggie meals I had in SF.All in all the Carlton was a fantastic place to stay and I heartily recommend it. We chose it based on all the reviews on TripAdvisor and similar sites, so our hopes were high - and we were far from disappointed. There are so many nice little touches that the staff seem to have put in place, the sort of thing that makes the overall experience that much nicer. Next time I visit San Francisco, whether for business or pleasure, I will definitely be staying at the Carlton again.	
