Sep 23 2008 	Great hotel	We stayed in this hotel instead of our previous SF choice as it was closer to the locations in SF that we were interested in.The first words we heard as we walked through the door were “welcome home”. Check in went very smoothly with no issues (we’d booked and prepaid via Airmiles). To the hotel’s eternal credit they were immediately honest about the local “no-go” area for tourists, pointing out to us on a map the location to avoid on foot and to be fair it’s unlikley that you would wander in that direction. If you heed this advice and take some sensible precautions (as you would anywhere else in the world), you should have no problems at all walking in the vicinity of the hotel. We didn’t encounter any issues, even though we always prefer to walk rather than take cabs.Although our room, on the 6th Floor, was at the front of the hotel overlooking Sutter St. and subtly lit by the neon hotel sign, we had no problems sleeping, even with open windows.We were up and about early on the Sunday to catch a tour bus at 8:30 and were mildly surprised to find that breakfast wasn’t available until 9:00 am. But you’re in San Francisco, so breakfast is always available somewhere (head down Sutter St. to Lou’s Diner and eat there would be our tip!)Returning to the hotel in the late afternoon, it was a nice touch to find complimentary wine on offer in the lobby for an hour or so - a perfect excuse to mix with the other guests.We did have breakfast in the Hotel’s Saha Restaurant the following day which provided a great start to the day - portion size, food quality and service were all good. The usual suspects are all on the menu.Check-out was as smooth as check-in. As other comments have noted, the hotel does include a $1 per night donation to a (very) local charity in your bill (and this was pointed out to us at check-in) – but if you’d rather not make this small donation then just say so.All in all, a quiet, clean, friendly hotel and a good base for exploring San Francisco’s sights.	
