Dec 19 2007 	Great Service Neat Hotel	We visited California in mid October and stayed at the Carlton for three nights. If you require very posh, five-star hotels, the Carlton is not for you. However, if you are attempting a trip to the Bay area and don't want to completely empty your wallet and you want to have a great time, then I heartily recommend the Carlton.People who complain about the neighborhood perplex me. This is the heart of a huge city. It was busy but not scary. I wouldn't recommend going out for a walk at 2:00 AM, but then I don't do that in my neighborhood, either.What I loved: The restaurant was great. The lobby was cozy and they treat you to wine around 5:30 PM before you go out. The rooms were very nicely appointed and very clean. The staff bring you a six pack of Pelligrino complimentary or a pitcher of filtered water -- your choice. The staff were truly wonderful. Very kind and very helpful in every way. The bed was very comfortable.What I didn't like: The walls were paper thin. This is a historic building with plaster walls. I felt like I had to whisper to talk late at night and likewise, we heard exactly what our neighbors were doing just before dawn...! Overall, for the price and the location (walking distance to Union Square and a long walk to Chinatown), I would certainly stay at the Carlton again.	
Dec 15 2007	A Great Place!	&quot;Ask and You Shall Receive&quot; must be the secret phrase of this fabulous budget priced, but clean and lovely hotel. I booked on line and got a fantastic deal of $82-$89 per night. When I called direct and spoke to Emilie to confirm some details, she offered to upgrade us (no charge)! She and Theo and Ben and all of the other staff there go out of their way to give you everything you need. The room was cold, so they brought me space heaters. Free wine is served every night and they also bring bottles to your room. Can't decide between red or white wine, okay, take both! I mentioned it was a special occasion and Theo made balloons appear! I can't understand the complaints about the decor -- it's new and clean and has a modern and international flair with a bit of an IKEA/Target/Pier 1 look, but if you want leather or antiques, go pay $300 a night for it. The bed was comfortable, the room was reasonably spacious, what more could you want? Yes, it borders the tenderloin, but so does the downtown area! Don't be scared off, it was totally fine. Easy access to transportation, parking via the hotel or across the street. We walked everywhere, including through the tenderloin (and we were two women together) and had no problems.	
Nov 22 2007	ALL hotels should be run like the Carlton!	Having just returned from a four-night stay at the Carlton, I am bewildered at some of the comments in other recent reviews.We could not ask more from a hotel. The lobby/reception is lovely and welcoming. The rooms are simply, but tastefully furnished (I do not have a problem with a logo of &quot;HC&quot;... being Hotel Carlton - perhaps they should have said &quot;Hotel Bed&quot; instead?)There are regular comments about the 'paper-thin walls'. We never had any real problems (though jetlag may have accounted for this), aside from early one evening when we could hear other guests in the hallway.The free wine tasting in the lobby is a lovely way to start the evening - and to my less than expert pallete were good quality wines as well, giving you a nice introduction to the wines of the region.I found the maps and comments in the lifts/elevators quite charming/amusing/informative myself, but perhaps this is a matter of personal choice.We did not eat at the restaurant (as we already had a number of places we wanted to visit), but the scents and smells coming from there were lovely.As regards the location, yes, this is a city-centre hotel and yes, it does border on the 'Tenderloin' district. So - quite simply - DON'T HEAD INTO THE TENDERLOIN! The staff will provide you with a map showing where the Tenderloin starts (NB. the streets south of the hotel). As there are three buses that head along Sutter Street, plus the cablecar is just a few blocks away, there is no real need to walk anyway.But the real stars of this hotel are the staff (especially Theo, but I don't want to lessen the praise for anyone else). Everyone is friendly and cannot do enough to help.The hotel also supports local homeless children and we were more than happy to have a Dollar a day added to our bill to help this worthy cause. We also added an extra gratuity to the bill to say thank you to the great staff.Should, as and when we come back to San Francisco, we would stay at the Carlton without a second thought. If only it had a pool, it would be perfect.	
