Nov 1 2007 	Reasonably Priced; Modest Hotel with Some Flair	I booked the first five days of my trip at The Orchard Hotel, but they were sold out for the weekend, and I had to move to the Carlton. The Carlton's weekend rate was the same via AAA that I booked during the week at the Orchard. For the price--during high season in the City--it was a good choice, but it definitely lacked the luxury touches of the Orchard. But to avoid comparisons, I'll review the Carlton on it's own merit.First of all, they've done a fabulous job with the lobby and the wine receptions, etc. The staff is really friendly and down to earth, and they were great about providing all the Joy of Life Club extras. When our welcome cosmopolitan cocktails failed to materialize, they made up for it with a whole bottle of wine. They also checked me in early and let me check out late on Sunday with no hassle. Loved that.Didn't try the restaurant, but the lobby was full on Saturday night of people waiting for tables, so I gather it's good. The food is Turkish or something along those lines.Our room was a twin, and while small, it was comfortable. No a/c, which wasn't a problem this trip, but I could see it being uncomfortable in warm weather. Luckily, the windows opened wide to nice city views.Our room (804) had a big walk-in closet, which made up for the lack of space in the room itself. The bathroom was tiny, and for someone with a lot of toiletries or makeup to spread around, it wouldn't be convenient. We managed, though.The beds were comfortable, although the linens are not the best of quality. Still, the decor is cute and eclectic, and these rooms are perfectly clean and adequate for younger clientele who are truly using the room as a place to sleep in between adventures within the City. The location, at the edge of the Tenderloin, is not as convenient as some other hotels closer to Nob Hill and Union Square, although you can still find public transportation within a few blocks. Hardier types might find the walk to Union Square and Chinatown do-able, but we're talking about 10-12 blocks up and down some pretty steep hills, each way. That's a long walk after a day of sight-seeing and loaded down with shopping bags or whatever. Overall, I think this hotel is great for younger singles, active travelers without kids, or active retirees...families would not be comfortable here, simply because there is no room to spread out at all. It's not particularly romantic, either--a bit on the spartan side for, say, a honeymoon hotel. But if you have limited funds and just really want to stay in the City, it might work for a couple wanting a romantic weekend on a budget.	
